definition.value: A rice powder derived from toasted rice.

Toasted-rice powder is a common pantry ingredient in Northern Thai and Lao cuisines, made by slowly toasting raw sticky rice to a deep golden brown, then grinding it into a coarse powder using a mortar and pestle or spice grinder. [https://www.seriouseats.com/recipes/2019/05/toasted-rice-powder-recipe.html]
Blood meal is a dry, inert powder made from blood used as a high-nitrogen organic fertilizer and a high protein animal feed.

It is one of the highest non-synthetic sources of nitrogen. It usually comes from cattle or hogs as a slaughterhouse by-product. N = 13.25%, P = 1.0%, K = 0.6%.

A pre-evisceration carcass is the carcass of a dead animal immediately following hide removal, before any antimicrobial applications and any part of the evisceration process has been performed. This is a material entity state within a butchery process.
A post-intervention carcass is a carcass that has had all antimicrobial intervention applied, been split in half along the backbone, and placed in a cooler, often referred to as the "hot box" cooler.
A cut of meat that is initially separated from the carcass of an animal during butchering.

Food trimmings are the parts removed from the culinary trimming of unwanted or inedible parts (i.e. sinews, skin, fat etc.) from meat, fish poultry or vegetables. Trimmings are used for making stocks, soups and sauces.
High-moisture corn refers to corn harvested at 24 percent or greater moisture, stored and allowed to ferment in a silo or other storage structure, and used as feed for livestock.
Rolled grain is grain has been mechanicallly crushed to separate the hull from the endosperm.

Corn stover consists of the leaves and stalks of maize (corn) (Zea mays ssp. mays L.) plants left in a field after harvest and consists of the residue: stalk; the leaf, husk, and cob remaining in the field following the harvest of cereal grain.
Such stover makes up about half of the yield of a corn crop and is similar to straw from other cereal grasses; in Britain it is sometimes called corn straw.
Corn stubble are the stems of corn plants remaining in the ground after harvest.
The outer coverings of the cottonseed, known as cottonseed hulls, are removed from the cotton kernels before the oil is extracted.
Cottonseed hulls serve as an excellent source of feed for the livestock as they contain about 8% of cotton linters which have nearly 100% cellulose in them.
Stubble which remains after harvesting soybeans.
A food product which has albacore tuna as a defining ingredient.
